{"type":"message","id":"d62d8101","parentId":"e85ce445","timestamp":"2026-06-05T08:14:55.445Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the actual data from the TikTok Hair Clips & Hair Pins category (nodeId=908552) in Vietnam:\n\nKey insights:\n1. **Average price: $27,758 VND (~$$1.11)** - This is the category average\n2. **Median price: $20,000 VND (~$0.80)** - Half of products are below this\n3. **Top50 products** show a mix of prices:\n   - $48,800 VND (~$$1.95) - 爪夹 (crab clip)\n   - $42,000 VND (~$1.68)\n   - $38,000 VND (~$1.52)\n   - $37,536 VND (~$1.50)\n   - $32,120 VND (~$1.28)\n   - $22,900 VND (~$0.92)\n   - $20,999 VND (~$0.84)\n   - $19,800 VND (~$0.79)\n   - $19,000 VND (~$0.76)\n   - $17,000 VND (~$0.68)\n   - $14,999 VND (~$0.60)\n   - $8,999 VND (~$0.36)\n\nThe real problem is that most of the top-performing items are clustered in the lower price range, which means the algorithm keeps surfacing budget-friendly options rather than the premium products the user actually wants to promote.\n\nLooking at the high-margin candidates that do exist—like the $1.95 crab clip, the $1.68 ribbon clip, and the $1.52 spotted clip—these have much better profit potential. The issue isn't that Sorftime lacks data on higher-priced items, but that I'm not filtering for them specifically. I need to set a price floor to exclude anything under $1.50, which would naturally surface the clips and accessories with actual growth potential. The price distribution across categories shows the 908552 node centers around $1.11, with the top performers ranging from $1.52 to $1.95—still modest but meaningfully higher. I should pull data from the Headbands node (605271) as well to compare price points across different accessory types and identify which category offers better margin potential.\n","thinkingSignature":"ef381a0c886c70b462bd4387725e7f7ac45305bbdf8fb2a970097823348bf39e"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_1d6ec86b492b4752965351c3","n