{"type":"message","id":"5dc589a6","parentId":"ad9bcfe0","timestamp":"2026-06-05T08:14:55.445Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is saying they have 29,845 calls remaining in their MCP quota, valid for one month, and they want me to use it freely (\"使劲用\" = use it aggressively).\n\nThis is important context - they have plenty of quota to work with. Let me now report back on what I found and then take action to find high-margin black horse products.\n\nLooking at the data:\n- VN Hair Clips: avg price $1.11, median $0.80 - too low\n- MY Hair Clips: avg price $4.24, median $2.52 - much better!\n- MY has products at $11.90, $2.80, $1.99 etc.\n\n\n- The MY market is clearly where the higher-value opportunities are\n\nThe real challenge is that category reports give me top sellers by volume, but I need to find emerging high-margin products. I should use the 29,845 call budget to systematically explore category reports across different sites and nodes, then filter for premium-priced items that have good ratings and recent growth momentum. The user wants me to be more aggressive with the quota, so I'm going to shift from just reporting to actively executing a discovery strategy.\n\nI can search by product name using `tiktok_similar_product` which supports site filtering, then apply price minimums. Or I could scan through category reports across multiple sites (VN, MY, ID, PH) to identify which ones have higher average prices, then drill into those specific categories. The MY Hair Clips category already showed promise with an average price of $4.24 and median of $2.52, which is significantly higher than other markets.\n\nGiven the monthly quota of 29,845 calls, I can afford to be more aggressive with my search strategy. I should scan multiple sites and categories systematically to find products priced above $3, then validate their growth metrics and margin potential before presenting findings to the user.\n","thinkingSignature":